@juguangliang Well, the code is a little complex. You need to modified several files. The central trick is about the `ReleaseAll` function in pooled_storage_manager. The hacking steps are as follows:
1. move the ReleaseAll function to public
2. write a correspoding `void RealeaseAll(int dev_id, int dev_type)` function in storage.cc. my code is 

```
void StorageImpl::ReleaseAll(int dev_id, int dev_type) {
    auto&& device = storage_managers_.at(dev_type);
    storage::StorageManager *maneger = device.Get(
            dev_id, []() {
            LOG(FATAL) <<  "Cannot Free space to a device you have not allocated";
            return nullptr;
        });
maneger->ReleaseAll();
}
```

yes, it is quite like the `Free` function, but `int dev_id, int dev_type` is easier to understand and it really frees memory rather than recycles memory.
3. use `Storage::Get()->ReleaseAll(som_dev_id, some_dev_type)` to free memory.
I have tested the code under some simple situations, like creating a NDArray an then deleting it. The code works. But when I wrote a python wrapper and used it in python ,it threw a memory exception. I didn't know why. As you see, this thread doesn't attract much attention of the core MXNet developers, so there might not be a perfect solution. Also, I think manually releasing the memory is not very safe in a very complex situation, so leting mxnet take the control maybe better. I suggest you the following way of getting rid of the memory problem.
1. use python to write your mxnet code
2. train the net using `commands.getstatusoutput('python your_model_file.py')`
you don't need to modified any source code and it also works.

